#In a file called my_clean place the command line that will 
#search for all files - in the current directory as well as 
#in its sub-directories - with a name ending by ~, or a name that start and end by
#The command line will print and delete all files found.
#Only one command is allowed: no ; or && or other gitaneries.

#Example 00

#$>my_clean
#./.zshrc~
#...
#./blah/#tat#
#$>
#Tip
#You should dig into the command find (man find)



find . ! -type d \( -iname \*\~ -o -iname \#\*\# \) -print -exec rm {} \;